data.title: Top 500 Fantasy Baseball Dynasty Rankings (July Update!)
data.meta_description: Want a competitive advantage in your league? Check out the Top 50 Fantasy Baseball Dynasty Rankings from Fantrax to get the edge you need.
data.text:
We’ve just passed the midway point of the 2024 season, and are careening towards the All-Star break faster than an Elly De La Cruz stolen-base attempt, which makes it the perfect time for a fresh Fantrax Top 500 Dynasty Rankings update. There’s been some significant movement at the top with the aforementioned De La Cruz, who reached the lofty 40-steal threshold by the conclusion of June, and fellow burgeoning superstar Gunnar Henderson — who wrapped up June with an astonishing 26 round-trippers, the second-most in the majors this season behind only Yankees icon Aaron Judge — joining Bobby Witt Jr. to form a new “big three” at the top of these rankings. The trio are all under the age of 25 and figure to remain locked into these spots, health permitting, for the next few years. There will be typical ebbs and flows for all three, but given their age and stratospheric talent, they’re pretty much locked in as top-10 overall dynasty assets until further notice.

There are plenty of additional dynasty-relevant storylines to focus on, which we’ll get to in a moment. However, it’s worth highlighting some of the established upper-echelon contributors that have suffered serious injuries this season, which has led to lenghty absences and resulted in their dynasty stock declining considerably from their lofty pre-season rankings. Some of those notable fantasy stars (and high-level prospects) include: Ronald Acuña Jr., Mookie Betts, Spencer Strider, Eury Pérez, Mike Trout, Josh Jung, Triston Casas, Jasson Domínguez, Jordan Lawlar, Devin Williams, Matt McLain, Xander Bogaerts, Christian Encarnacion-Strand, Jesús Luzardo, Kodai Senga, Kyle Bradish, Shane Bieber and Jett Williams.

We’ve also witnessed the overwhelming majority of potential 2024 impact prospects reaching the majors prior to the Midsummer Classic with consensus top-ranked dynasty prospect James Wood finally ascending to the majors on July 1. His arrival means that there has been a changing of the guard at the top of the Fantrax Top 500 non-debuted top prospects list with Orioles third baseman Coby Mayo taking over the top spot. Here’s the latest top-12 non-debuted prospect list:

1. Coby Mayo, 3B, Orioles

2. Carson Williams, SS, Rays

3. Colt Emerson, SS, Mariners

4. Jackson Jobe, P, Tigers

5. Lazaro Montes, OF, Mariners

6. Emmanuel Rodriguez, OF, Twins

7. Dylan Crews, OF, Nationals

8. Walker Jenkins, OF, Twins

9. Samuel Basallo, C/1B, Orioles,

10. Noah Schultz, P, White Sox

11. Xavier Isaac, 1B, Rays

12. Matt Shaw, 3B, Cubs

Without further delay, here are the latest Fantrax Top 500 Overall Dynasty rankings. Please enjoy it responsibly.

Ready to make the 2024 MLB season the best yet? Fantrax offers a fantasy baseball league for everyone. Want to get started right away? Then jump into a Best Ball League or a Draft and Hold. Maybe you have an existing league but want the most customizable fantasy baseball platform in existence? Then you definitely need to check out the Fantrax Commissioner! And of course, whether you play roto or points, you can head to the Fantrax Mock Draft Lobby to start your draft prep for the 2024 fantasy baseball season.

About the Rankings

Before we delve into the Top 500 Dynasty Rankings, here are a few critical caveats.

These rankings are exclusively for long-term dynasty fantasy leagues. They’re merely a snapshot in time and will change dramatically as the 2024 campaign progresses.

These rankings are designed for traditional 16-team dynasty leagues with standard 5×5 (non-OBP) rotisserie scoring with weekly lineup periods where players can be rostered indefinitely without contracts or salaries.

Park factors, team context, immediate role, and other present variables matter but aren’t weighed heavily in these rankings when determining long-term player value, especially when it comes to prospects. If a young player is talented enough, they’ll get an opportunity sooner or later, regardless of how cluttered their immediate path to playing time is at the moment.

Flags Fly Forever. The primary goal is to build a sustainable contending roster without completely mortgaging the future. Your roster’s proximity to the contending or rebuilding ends of the spectrum has a significant impact on whether someone like Jacob deGrom or Ethan Salas makes more sense for your roster.

Do your own research. Draw your own conclusions. These rankings are an excellent starting point, but fantasy managers should seek out alternative sources of information. At the end of the day, it’s your roster.

The further you traverse down this list, the larger the positional tiers become and the margin between players becomes razor-thin. Here’s an oversimplification: the gap between the 300th player and the 325th is so small that it really comes down to a difference of opinion when making a value judgment.

These rankings do not include players currently under investigation by law enforcement or Major League Baseball.

Without further delay, here is the FanTrax Top 500 list. Enjoy. If you have any questions or comments, feel free to reach out to me on X (formerly Twitter) @GeorgeBissell.
